        "creatureType": "",
        "details": {
            "description": "<p>Daemonic curses slither and crawl through malevolent runes carved in four stone pillars. HP is per-pillar.</p>",
            "disable": "<p>DC 17 Thievery (trained) to scratch out a pillar&rsquo;s runes, dispel magic (1st level; counteract DC 15) to counteract a pillar&rsquo;s magic, or DC 18 Athletics (Force Open) to push a pillar over. Disabling a pillar requires two actions. Disabling all four pillars or slaying Sezruth disables the trap</p>",
            "isComplex": true,
            "level": 1,
            "reset": "",
            "routine": "<p><strong><span class=\"fontstyle0\">Routine </span></strong><span class=\"fontstyle2\"><strong>(4 actions):</strong> The trap loses 1 action each turn for each disabled pillar. On its initiative, the trap uses each action to afflict a different non-evil creature in the room with thirst. The creature must attempt a <span data-pf2-saving-throw=\"fortitude\" data-pf2-traits=\"\" data-pf2-label=\"\" data-pf2-dc=\"17\" data-pf2-show-dc=\"gm\">Fortitude save</span>.</span></p>\n<hr />\n<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\"><strong>Critical Success:</strong> </span><span class=\"fontstyle2\">The creature is temporarily immune to additional negative effects from the foretold ruin hazard's reaction for 24 hours. The hazard has no awareness of this immunity and continues to target this creature.</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\"><strong>Success:</strong> </span><span class=\"fontstyle2\">The creature is unaffected.</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\"><strong>Failure:</strong> </span><span class=\"fontstyle2\">The creature is @Compendium[pf2e.conditionitems.Fatigued]{Fatigued} until they drink water.</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"fontstyle2\">If the creature was already fatigued, they take [[/r 1d6 #nonlethal mental]] nonlethal mental damage.</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\"><strong>Critical Failure:</strong> </span><span class=\"fontstyle2\">The creature is fatigued until they drink water and takes 1d6 nonlethal mental damage. If the creature was already fatigued, they instead take [[/r 2d6 #nonlethal mental]] nonlethal mental damage.</span></p>"
        },
